# How Did Sojourner Truth Escape Slavery? A Detailed Report

Sojourner Truth, born Isabella Baumfree around 1797 in Swartekill, Ulster County, New York, was a remarkable African-American woman who escaped the brutal conditions of slavery and rose to become a powerful abolitionist and women's rights activist. Her escape from slavery was not only a pivotal moment in her life but also a significant event that shaped her future activism and legacy. This report provides a comprehensive and detailed examination of how Sojourner Truth escaped slavery, drawing from multiple reliable sources to present an in-depth narrative.

## Early Life and Enslavement

Isabella Baumfree was born into slavery to parents James and Elizabeth Baumfree, who were themselves slaves on the estate of Colonel Johannes Hardenbergh in Swartekill, New York. She was the youngest of approximately 12 siblings. The family spoke Dutch as their first language, which Isabella also learned before acquiring English later in life. At the age of nine, following the death of her original owner, she was sold at auction to John Neely for $100, a price that included a herd of sheep. This sale marked the beginning of a series of ownership changes, during which she endured harsh treatment and physical abuse ([KidsKonnect](https://kidskonnect.com/people/sojourner-truth/); [Biography Online](https://www.biographyonline.net/women/sojourner-truth-biography.html)).

## Conditions Leading to Escape

Isabella was sold multiple times: after John Neely, she was sold to Martinus Schryver in 1808 for $105, and then again two years later. During this period, she was forced to marry an older slave named Thomas Dumont (or Dumont), with whom she had several children. Dumont promised her freedom but later broke this promise, continuing to hold her in bondage. The breaking of this promise, combined with the harsh treatment she endured, motivated Isabella to seek freedom for herself and her family ([SoftSchools Timeline](https://www.softschools.com/viewTimeline.action?id=57); [KidsKiddle](https://kids.kiddle.co/Sojourner_Truth)).

## The Escape: Circumstances and Process

In 1826, a year before New York's law emancipating slaves took effect (July 4, 1827), Isabella made the courageous decision to escape slavery. She fled with her infant daughter, Sophia, seeking refuge with the Van Wagenen family, who were abolitionists and sympathetic to her plight. Dumont attempted to reclaim Sophia, but the Van Wagenens intervened and paid Dumont $20 for Isabella's freedom, effectively purchasing her emancipation before the state law officially freed her ([KidsKonnect](https://kidskonnect.com/people/sojourner-truth/); [Women's History](https://www.womenshistory.org/education-resources/biographies/sojourner-truth)).

This escape was significant not only because it was a physical act of liberation but also because it took place within the context of a changing legal environment. New York State was moving toward abolition, but the law's delayed implementation meant that Isabella's freedom was not guaranteed without direct intervention. The Van Wagenen family's support was crucial in securing her freedom legally and physically.

## Legal Victory: Recovery of Her Son

After gaining her freedom, Sojourner Truth took the extraordinary step of legally challenging the illegal sale of her son, Peter, who had been sold into slavery in Alabama. She became the first black woman to win a court case against a white man when she successfully sued for Peter's return. This legal victory was groundbreaking and demonstrated her determination and courage in fighting for her family's freedom and rights ([KidsKonnect](https://kidskonnect.com/people/sojourner-truth/); [Women's History](https://www.womenshistory.org/education-resources/biographies/sojourner-truth)).

## Name Change and Spiritual Calling

In 1843, Isabella Baumfree changed her name to Sojourner Truth, signifying her new mission as a traveling preacher and advocate for abolition and women's rights. This change was inspired by a profound religious experience while living with the Van Wagenen family. She felt called by the Spirit to preach the truth and fight injustice, which she pursued with vigor for the rest of her life ([KidsKonnect](https://kidskonnect.com/people/sojourner-truth/); [Women's History](https://www.womenshistory.org/education-resources/biographies/sojourner-truth)).

